{ The Exchange Variation in the Morphy Defense is one of the unpleasant scenarios for White and it is one of the alternative variations to the mainline and the closed variation. The reason why I report here this variation is only to show why it is a bad idea for White to take the bait and capture the Black Knight. Move Bxc6. }
3. Bxc6 { White Bishop takes the bait and moves Bxc6 capturing the Black Knight. } 3... dxc6 { Black replies with dxc6 ruining his Pawn structure in exchange for a Bishop. Black could have made the move bxc6 which, however, would have led to moves d4, exd4, and Qxd4 which gave White control of the center. Instead, the move dxc6 opens the diagonal c8-h3 to the bishop and the d-column to the queen. White move Nxe5. } 4. Nxe5 { At this point, the White Knight captures the pawn on e5 with the move Nxe5 and, at the same time, threatens the pawn on c6. } { [%cal Re5c6] } 4... Qd4 { The Black Queen will reply with Qd4 by attacking both the White Pawn on e4 and the White Knight on e5 in the center. In addition, it will also put pressure on the d2 pawn on the White Queen line. Not a favorable line for White that is force to move Nf3. } { [%cal Rd4e4,Rd4e5,Rd4d2] } 5. Nf3 { The White Knight is forced to move Nc3 attacking the Queen. } { [%cal Rf3d4] } 5... Qxe4+ { The Black Queen will capture the pawn with Qxe4+ controlling the center threatening the White Knight and checking the King. It's clear then that the Exchange Variation is not a good alternative for White. } { [%cal Re4f3] } *


